qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      2NT Overcalls Over Weak Two Bids     }
^-|cs||fp||ht|c|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|For my intermediate students, this is one of the most misunderstood calls in bridge. A 2NT overcall after a one-level opening is indeed the "Unusual notrump" for the two lowest unbid suits. But a 2NT overcall after the opponents' weak two-bid is anything but Unusual. |
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

It is natural and balanced. It guarantees a stopper in the opponent's suit. The range is that of a strong 1NT opener'maybe a little stronger. I'd say it is at least 15 and could be up to 19. In the balancing seat, it is (as usual) about a king less (still natural, balanced and with a stopper). And again, play "Systems On" ' Stayman, Jacoby, etc.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: Unlike what Cohen recommends, Howard plays that a 2NT bid in the balancing seat over a weak 2 (e.g. 2H-P-P-2N) still shows a strong NT (15-18 or so) not 12-15.^*N|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


