qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      4NT Overcalls     }
^-|cs||fp||ht|c|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Finally, we have a notrump overcall that is not natural. In general, a 4NT overcall is for the minors. After the opponents' 4@H opening, I'd overcall 4NT with:|ht|f|at|^B|ih|pS7H2DA Q J 9 8 7CK Q J 6 5|AT|

It shows at least 5-5 shape. Again there are many complexities (really, 4NT can be any 2 suits), but this article can't go on forever. What's written here is sufficient for my "summary approach."|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|In general, a 4N overcall is 5-5 in the minors (assuming the opening bid was in a major). However, there is one exception. If the opponents open 4@S, then 4N shows any 5/5 hand. The suits are not necessarily the minors; one of the suits could be hearts. Therefore, responder must take that into account when bidding. Responder should only bid 5@D over 4N if he is willing to hear partner correct to 5@H. Otherwise he should bid 5@C even if he has better diamonds.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


