qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|b|at|^-{      1X-P-1Y-1N     }
^-|cs||fp||ht|c|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Note: Make sure your partnership discusses what 1NT means in this auction:|ht|f|cs|6|
at|^B{|ia|1cp1s1n|at|}|ht|f|at|^k@2Is 1NT natural, strong (15-18) with stoppers?  Or, is it a light takeout for the unbid suits?  These days, I recommend the former (strong) -- and, of course, systems on if North continues.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


ht|i|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Playing this as a strong NT (15-18) is fine. However, it is slightly dangerous. In general, the opponents have at least 20 HCP between them, often more. Therefore partner rates to be weak so you could easily be in trouble in 1NT. Therefore many good players play this as a "sandwich NT." It is defined as a weak takeout bid, less than an opening hand. Usually with 5 cards in the unbid minor and 4 cards in the unbid major. With a stronger hand and the 2 unbid suits, you can still make a takeout double.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


